# Retail Business Intelligence Dashboard Report

## Introduction

This project centers on building a Power BI dashboard with the Superstore dataset. The goal? Take raw retail data and actually make sense of it—to reveal the kind of insights managers need when they're making tough calls.

The dashboard digs into sales, profit, product performance, how different regions stack up, and where sales trends have been heading.

## Project Objectives

Here's what this project set out to do:

- Break down the overall sales and profit numbers.
- Figure out which regions are leading in both sales and profit.
- Identify top-performing product categories.
- Explore changes in sales over time—spotting patterns and jumps.
- Pinpoint which regions need more attention and creative solutions.
- Lay out what the business should do next to keep growing.

# Key Findings

## Overall Business Performance

| Metric | Value |
|----------|----------|
| Total Sales | $2.30 Million |
| Total Profit | $286,397 |
| Total Orders | 9,994 |

Sales are solid, and the profit margin looks healthy.

## Regional Performance

| Region | Sales ($) | Profit ($) |
|---------|-----------:|-----------:|
| West | 725,458 | 108,418 |
| East | 678,781 | 91,523 |
| Central | 501,240 | 39,706 |
| South | 391,722 | 46,749 |

### Insight

The West tops the list—most sales and the strongest profit, with the East trailing just behind.

Central shows okay sales but lower profits.

The South lags behind—both in sales and profit—so that region needs a boost.

## Product Category Performance

| Category | Sales ($) | Profit ($) |
|------------|-----------:|-----------:|
| Technology | 836,154 | 145,455 |
| Furniture | 742,000 | 18,451 |
| Office Supplies | 719,047 | 122,491 |

### Insight

Technology leads the pack, both in revenue and profit.

Office Supplies does well in profit, even if its sales in dollars don't top Technology.

Furniture pulls in plenty of sales, but its profit is unimpressive—probably too many discounts or higher costs cutting into margins.

## Sales Trend Analysis

| Year | Sales ($) |
|------|-----------:|
| 2014 | 484,247 |
| 2015 | 470,533 |
| 2016 | 609,206 |
| 2017 | 733,215 |

### Insight

2015 saw a small dip, but 2016 and especially 2017 picked up a lot.

Sales hit their highest mark in 2017—clearly, growth is the trend over these years.

# Recommendations

## Double Down on Winning Regions

The business should keep investing in the West and East. These two regions drive most of the sales and profit.

## Give Extra Focus to South and Central

South and Central need attention—consider sharper marketing, targeted promos, and new ways to engage local customers.

## Make Technology Products the Star

Keep Technology at the center of the offer. The numbers speak for themselves; that category is the revenue and profit engine.

## Rethink Furniture Strategy

Low profit on Furniture stands out.

Management should take a close look at prices, discounting, and costs in this segment—it's time to rethink the approach and get more out of these sales.

## Turn Sales Trends into Action

Use what's working.

The strong upward trend in recent years means there's room to tighten up forecasting, keep inventory right-sized, and plan for growth.

# Conclusion

Power BI brought the data to life.

The big picture: West and Technology are carrying the business right now.

There's still work to do in Furniture, and both South and Central offer growth potential if approached differently.

Following the right steps based on these findings will help keep growth steady—and make profits stronger.

